After his time with the Jets, Shuler played for the Houston Texans and the Tennessee Titans. He is remembered for his powerful running style and his contributions to the Mountaineers' success.
Cargill Falls Mill: Cargill Falls Mill, located in Cargill, Minnesota, is a historic water-powered mill built in 1854 by John Cargill. Originally used for grinding wheat, the mill played a pivotal role in the region's early agricultural development. It served as a community hub and a symbol of the town's prosperity. The mill ceased operation in the early 20th century, but its structure remains standing as a testament to the area's past.  The mill, now privately owned, is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
University of Naples \"L'Orientale\": The University of Naples "L'Orientale" is a public research university in Naples, Italy, specializing in the study of Asia, Africa, and the Middle East. Founded in 1732 by Charles III of Bourbon as the "Royal Institute of Oriental Languages", it is one of the oldest and most prestigious institutions for Oriental studies in Europe. The university boasts a renowned faculty and diverse student body, offering a wide range of undergraduate and postgraduate programs in languages, cultures, history, and international relations related to the Eastern world. Notable alumni include prominent scholars, diplomats, and politicians who have contributed significantly to the field of Oriental studies.
2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup: The 2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup was the 17th edition of the biennial men's national football championship for the North American, Central American, and Caribbean nations affiliated with CONCACAF.  Held from June 16 to July 16, 2023, the tournament featured 16 teams competing in matches across the United States and Canada.  Mexico won the tournament, defeating Panama in the final, marking their ninth Gold Cup title.  The tournament also saw the emergence of young American stars like Brandon Vazquez and Alejandro Zendejas, highlighting the growing talent pool in North American football.
Mary Is Coming: "Mary Is Coming" is a popular gospel song written by the American gospel singer and songwriter, Albert E. Brumley, in 1937.  The song, a hymn of anticipation and joy, has become a staple in many Christian denominations, particularly in the Pentecostal and gospel music traditions.  Brumley's lyrics depict a scene of Christ's second coming, with the return of Mary, a symbolic representation of the Virgin Mary, heralding the arrival of the Messiah. The song's simple melody and powerful lyrics have resonated with believers for generations, making it one of the most recognizable and enduring hymns in American gospel music.
Vladislav Romanov: Vladislav Romanov (1917-1992) was the youngest son of Grand Duke Kirill Vladimirovich of Russia and his wife, Grand Duchess Victoria Feodorovna. Born into the Russian Imperial family during a period of great political upheaval, Vladislav's life was marked by exile and personal tragedy. He and his family spent much of their lives in Europe, first in Finland, and later in France, where he became a respected scientist and published extensively on his research. Following the death of his elder brother, Vladimir Kirillovich, in 1992, Vladislav became the titular head of the Romanov family, though his claim to the Russian throne was disputed by other branches of the family.
Sir James Heath, 1st Baronet: Sir James Heath, 1st Baronet (1757–1834) was a prominent British engraver and painter. Born in London, he was the son of a successful engraver and received his early training from his father. Heath became known for his high-quality engravings of portraits, landscapes, and historical subjects. He was a member of the Royal Academy of Arts and served as its Engraver for over 30 years. He was knighted in 1814 and elevated to the baronetcy in 1831, reflecting his significant contributions to the arts. Heath's work is characterized by its precision, detail, and sensitivity, showcasing his mastery of the engraving technique. He remains an influential figure in the history of British engraving.
Viktor Shuvalov: Viktor Shuvalov (born 1956) is a prominent Russian businessman and former government official. He served as First Deputy Prime Minister of Russia under Prime Minister Vladimir Putin from 2008 to 2012. Prior to that, Shuvalov held several high-ranking positions within the Russian government, including Minister of Energy and Head of the Presidential Property Management Department. He is known for his close ties to President Putin and his role in overseeing major state-owned companies. Shuvalov is also a prominent figure in the Russian business world, holding significant stakes in various companies and serving on numerous corporate boards.
Zanthoxylum pinnatum: *Zanthoxylum pinnatum*, commonly known as the **prickly ash**, is a species of flowering plant in the citrus family, Rutaceae. Native to tropical and subtropical regions of Africa, Asia, and Australia, this tree is notable for its aromatic leaves and fruits. The species is valued for its medicinal properties, with its bark, leaves, and fruits used in traditional medicine to treat a variety of ailments, including digestive issues, skin conditions, and pain relief. *Zanthoxylum pinnatum* is also a significant source of timber and a popular choice for ornamental landscaping. Its thorns, however, make it unsuitable for areas with high foot traffic.
Nathan Massengill: Nathan Massengill (born October 20, 1988) is an American professional baseball pitcher. He was drafted by the Tampa Bay Rays in the 12th round of the 2010 MLB Draft and made his Major League Baseball (MLB) debut with the Rays in 2015. Massengill has also played for the Chicago White Sox, Philadelphia Phillies, and Boston Red Sox. Known for his slider and changeup, he has primarily served as a relief pitcher throughout his career. Notably, he pitched in the 2015 American League Wild Card Game for the Tampa Bay Rays.
Mike Papantonio: Mike Papantonio is an American trial lawyer, legal commentator, and television personality, best known for his role as a legal analyst on the cable news channel, MSNBC. He is also the founder and managing partner of the law firm, Papantonio &  Associates, which specializes in class action and mass tort lawsuits. Papantonio rose to prominence in the 1990s after winning several high-profile cases, including the $4 billion settlement against the tobacco industry. His outspoken and often controversial opinions on legal issues and his strong advocacy for consumer rights have made him a popular figure in both legal and media circles.
Oasis (2017 film): "Oasis" is a 2017 American romantic drama film directed by Ivana Trumbo. The film follows the story of two estranged siblings, played by Shea Whigham and Brittany Snow, who reconnect after years of separation when their father, played by the late James Caan, is diagnosed with a terminal illness. The film explores themes of family, forgiveness, and second chances, with a backdrop of the Arizona desert. Notably, "Oasis" is Ivana Trumbo's directorial debut and was filmed on location in Arizona, highlighting the state's natural beauty and diverse landscapes.
Michelle Zatlyn: Michelle Zatlyn is a Canadian-American entrepreneur and technology executive best known as the co-founder and CEO of Cloudflare, a global network that provides content delivery, security, and performance services for websites and applications. Zatlyn co-founded Cloudflare in 2009 alongside Matthew Prince and Lee Holloway, with the mission to build a better and more secure internet. Under her leadership, Cloudflare has grown significantly, becoming a critical infrastructure provider for millions of websites and apps worldwide. Zatlyn is recognized for her contributions to the tech industry, including being named one of Fortune's "Most Powerful Women in Business" in 2022.
Fairview Township, Fayette County, India: Fairview Township is a township in Fayette County, Indiana, United States.  The township was established in 1827 and encompasses a land area of 36 square miles. Notable features include the historical Fairview Cemetery, established in the late 19th century, and the annual Fairview Township Fall Festival, a popular community event held each October. The township is primarily agricultural, with a growing residential population and a rich history dating back to the early settlement of Indiana.
Hodgson's brown-toothed shrew: Hodgson's brown-toothed shrew (**_Crocidura Hodgsonii_**) is a small, insectivorous mammal found in the Himalayas and surrounding regions of Asia. It is characterized by its brown fur, short tail, and distinctive brown teeth. First described by Brian Houghton Hodgson in 1836, this shrew is considered a common species throughout its range, inhabiting a variety of habitats from forests to grasslands.  Hodgson's brown-toothed shrew plays an important role in the ecosystem as a predator of insects and other invertebrates, helping to regulate their populations.
Hendrick Motorsports: Hendrick Motorsports is a prominent American professional stock car racing team based in Concord, North Carolina. Founded in 1984 by Rick Hendrick, the team has achieved immense success in NASCAR, winning a record 14 NASCAR Cup Series championships, most recently in 2021 with Kyle Larson. The team is known for its consistent performance and has fielded legendary drivers like Jeff Gordon, Jimmie Johnson, and Dale Earnhardt Jr., winning over 200 races across multiple series. Hendrick Motorsports has become synonymous with excellence in NASCAR, leaving a lasting legacy on the sport.
Pop (Pakistani TV channel): "Pop" is a Pakistani television channel launched in 2004 by the ARY Digital Network.  It caters to a younger demographic with a focus on entertainment programming, including music videos, reality shows, drama series, and film premieres. The channel gained significant popularity for its innovative content and its focus on promoting Pakistani music and artists. Notable figures associated with Pop include the popular Pakistani singer-songwriter Atif Aslam, whose music videos were frequently aired on the channel. Pop continues to be a major player in Pakistani television, contributing to the development and popularity of Pakistani entertainment.
WTCO: WTCO is a radio station based in Toledo, Ohio, broadcasting a classic hits format.  It was originally founded in 1941 as WSPD, and its call sign was changed to WTCO in 1979.  The station has a long history of local programming, featuring popular DJs like Dave "The Weasel" Wilson and the "Morning Zoo" team.  WTCO is owned by iHeartMedia, and its studios are located in downtown Toledo.
Larpent, Victoria: Victoria Larpent (1792-1882) was a British author and playwright known for her historical novels and plays set in the 17th and 18th centuries. Born into a literary family, she was the daughter of the playwright and dramatist, Francis Larpent, and the niece of the playwright, John O'Keeffe. Larpent's works often explored themes of love, duty, and social class, drawing on her extensive knowledge of history and costume. Her most notable novel, "The Heart of London" (1846), is a romantic tale set in the time of Charles II and reflects her interest in the historical period.
HMNZS Wellington (F69): HMNZS *Wellington* (F69) was a guided missile frigate of the Royal New Zealand Navy (RNZN) that served from 1988 to 2017. The ship was built in the United Kingdom and was part of the Leander-class frigate design. *Wellington* was named after the capital city of New Zealand and was the third ship of the Royal New Zealand Navy to bear the name. Notable features of the ship included the ability to launch Sea Skua anti-ship missiles and the modernized combat system known as the "ANZAC" upgrade. Throughout her service, *Wellington* participated in various operations, including the Gulf War, the Solomon Islands intervention, and maritime security patrols in the South Pacific.
1990 Back Bay, Massachusetts, train coll: The 1990 Back Bay train collision occurred on February 16, 1990, in Boston, Massachusetts, when two commuter trains collided head-on in the Back Bay station. The accident resulted in one fatality and over 170 injuries. It was attributed to a combination of factors, including a signal malfunction, a train engineer's failure to heed a warning signal, and a lack of adequate safety protocols. The collision led to a significant public outcry and a series of safety improvements implemented by the MBTA, including upgrades to signaling systems and increased operator training. The incident remains a stark reminder of the importance of safety in rail transportation.
Red Dirt \u2013 Red Heart: "Red Dirt – Red Heart" is a 2001 album by the American country music singer-songwriter, Toby Keith. Released on his own label, Show Dog Records, it was the album that cemented Keith's status as a major force in the contemporary country music scene. The album featured several hit singles, including "My List," "Who's Your Daddy," and "Beer for My Horses," which became a patriotic anthem after the 9/11 attacks. "Red Dirt – Red Heart" became Keith's most successful album to date, selling over 5 million copies in the United States and earning him his first Grammy Award nomination for Best Country Album.
Electronics industry in South Korea: The electronics industry in South Korea has been a cornerstone of the country's economic development since the 1960s.  Fueled by government initiatives, such as the "Heavy and Chemical Industry Promotion Plan," and a skilled workforce, South Korea established itself as a leading manufacturer of consumer electronics, semiconductors, and telecommunications equipment.  Companies like Samsung and LG have become global giants, renowned for their innovative products and technological prowess.  The industry's success has significantly contributed to South Korea's transformation into a high-income nation, making it a major player in the global electronics market.
Gulshan Rai Khatri: Gulshan Rai Khatri (1942-2018) was an Indian politician and a prominent figure in the Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh (RSS). He served as the national general secretary of the RSS from 1997 to 2002, a crucial period in the organization's expansion and political influence. Khatri was known for his strong organizational skills and his ability to bridge the gap between the RSS and its political wing, the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP). He played a significant role in shaping the RSS's agenda, particularly in areas like education and social outreach, and his contributions continue to be felt within the organization.
Marion Wilberforce: Marion Wilberforce (1837-1923) was a prominent British social reformer and philanthropist known for her tireless advocacy for the education and welfare of women. A devout Christian and daughter of the renowned abolitionist William Wilberforce, Marion dedicated her life to improving the lives of women in Victorian society. She founded and led several organizations, including the National Society for Women's Suffrage and the Ladies' Association for the Care of the Poor, tirelessly working for women's rights, including the right to education and employment. Her contributions extended to the establishment of numerous girls' schools across England, leaving a lasting legacy on the social landscape of the era.
Pana Sankranti: Pana Sankranti, also known as Magha Sankranti, is a Hindu festival celebrated in India, particularly in Odisha and West Bengal, marking the transition of the Sun from Capricorn to Aquarius. It falls on the first day of the month of Magha in the Hindu calendar, typically in January or February. The festival is marked by bathing in holy rivers, offering prayers to Surya (the Sun God), and enjoying traditional foods like 'pana' (a sweet drink made from jaggery and rice). It is believed to be a time for purification and a fresh start, symbolizing the victory of light over darkness. Notable figures associated with Pana Sankranti include the deities Surya and Vishnu, who are worshipped during the festivities.
Russell Doolittle: Russell Doolittle (1931-2020) was an American biochemist known for his pioneering work in protein evolution and the development of methods for protein sequence analysis. His research focused on the evolution of proteins, particularly fibrinogen and its relationship to other proteins in the blood clotting cascade. Doolittle's contributions led to the establishment of the "Doolittle Hypothesis," which proposes that fibrinogen evolved from a duplication of an ancestral gene. He also developed the "Doolittle Plot," a widely used tool for comparing protein sequences and identifying evolutionary relationships. His work has been fundamental in understanding the evolution of protein families and the structure and function of blood clotting proteins.
Melanie Johnston-Hollitt: Melanie Johnston-Hollitt is a prominent Australian astrophysicist renowned for her pioneering research in radio astronomy. Her work focuses on understanding the evolution of galaxies, particularly through the study of radio emission from active galactic nuclei. Johnston-Hollitt played a key role in the development of the Australian Square Kilometre Array Pathfinder (ASKAP), a cutting-edge radio telescope array, and has served as a leader in the international science community, including as the Director of the CSIRO Astronomy and Space Science division. She is a recipient of numerous awards, including the prestigious Pawsey Medal, for her significant contributions to the field of radio astronomy.
Adam Dennis: Adam Dennis is a British actor known for his roles in theatre, film, and television. He gained recognition for his portrayal of the character "Simon" in the popular television series "EastEnders" from 2006 to 2008.  Dennis's theatrical work includes notable performances in productions like "The History Boys" and "The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time." He is also recognized for his role as "Dr. Liam Fox" in the BBC medical drama "Holby City".  Dennis has received several accolades for his work, including a nomination for the Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role for his performance in "The History Boys."
Primula aureata: *Primula aureata*, commonly known as the golden primrose or Himalayan primrose, is a species of flowering plant in the primrose family, Primulaceae. Native to the Himalayas, this species is notable for its vibrant, golden-yellow flowers that bloom in spring.  The plant's popularity in horticulture stems from its striking appearance, ease of cultivation, and adaptability to various climates. *Primula aureata* was first described by the botanist John Forbes Royle in 1839, and since then, several varieties and cultivars have been developed.
There Is a Season: "There Is a Season" is a popular phrase from the biblical book of Ecclesiastes, specifically chapter 3, verses 1-8.  The passage describes the cyclical nature of life, highlighting various stages and events that occur in their own time. The phrase is often used to convey the idea that everything has its place and time, including joy, sorrow, war, peace, birth, and death. It is a reminder to accept the impermanence of life and to embrace each season with its unique opportunities and challenges.  The passage's wisdom has resonated with people across cultures and throughout history, becoming a common theme in literature, music, and everyday conversation.
Darlaston Town (1874) F.C. was a football club based in Darlaston, Staffordshire, England, founded in 1874. The club, originally known as Darlaston Town, was a founding member of the Birmingham Football Association and later joined the Staffordshire County Football Association. They achieved significant local success, winning the Staffordshire Senior Cup twice in 1900 and 1902. However, Darlaston Town eventually disbanded in 1914 due to the outbreak of World War I. Despite a short lifespan, the club played a role in the early development of football in the West Midlands region.
Jason McCaslin: Jason McCaslin is a contemporary American artist known for his large-scale, intricately detailed paintings and sculptures. His work often explores themes of nature, mythology, and the human condition, drawing inspiration from sources ranging from ancient Greek myths to contemporary pop culture. McCaslin's distinctive style is characterized by bold colors, meticulous brushwork, and a blend of realism and surrealism. He has exhibited his work extensively in galleries and museums both in the United States and abroad, garnering critical acclaim and recognition for his unique artistic vision.
Pantar: Pantar is a small island in the Lesser Sunda Islands of Indonesia, located east of Flores and north of Alor. The island is known for its rugged terrain, with active volcanoes and dense forests covering much of its surface. Pantar is home to the indigenous Pantar people, whose unique culture and traditions have been preserved for centuries. Notable historical figures from the island include Willem van der Does, the Dutch Governor-General of the East Indies in the 16th century. Pantar's economy is largely based on agriculture, fishing, and tourism, which has been increasing in recent years.
Natalia Pushkina: Natalia Pushkina (1836-1913) was a Russian writer, poet, and socialite, known primarily for her close relationship with her famed grandfather, Alexander Pushkin. She was born into a prominent family and inherited her grandfather's literary talent, writing poetry and prose throughout her life. While her work didn't achieve the same level of fame as Pushkin's, it offered valuable insight into the life and legacy of the renowned poet. Natalia Pushkina was also a significant figure in Russian social circles, known for her wit, intelligence, and passionate advocacy for education and women's rights.
Staniszcze Wielkie: Staniszcze Wielkie is a village located in the southeastern part of Poland, within the administrative district of Gmina Kobylanka, part of Stargard County in the West Pomeranian Voivodeship. The village is situated approximately 14 kilometers (9 miles) southeast of Stargard Szczeciński and 46 kilometers (29 miles) east of Szczecin, the regional capital. Staniszcze Wielkie holds historical significance as it was a major center for the production of pottery during the 18th and 19th centuries, with local artisans producing distinctive hand-painted ceramics. Today, the village is a popular destination for tourists seeking to experience traditional Polish rural life and explore its rich cultural heritage.
Konye: "Konye" is a term with multiple meanings, most notably referring to a traditional African name, often found in regions like South Africa and Nigeria. It can also denote a specific location, such as Konye, a village in the Democratic Republic of Congo. In South African culture, "Konye" is associated with the Xhosa language and is often given to boys. In the realm of art and literature, "Konye" may be referenced as a character, symbol, or theme in various creative works. While its specific meaning can vary based on context, "Konye" generally signifies a sense of tradition, cultural heritage, and personal identity within African communities.
Cyprus at the 2004 Summer Paralympics: Cyprus participated in the 2004 Summer Paralympics in Athens, Greece, marking its debut at the Paralympic Games. The Cypriot delegation consisted of six athletes competing in three sports: athletics, swimming, and table tennis.  The team's performance was highlighted by the bronze medal win by Andreas Makris in the men's 100m T46 race, a landmark achievement for Cyprus in Paralympic history. This participation was a significant step for the nation in establishing its presence on the international Paralympic stage and fostering a culture of inclusivity and athletic excellence.
Arnie (video game): "Arnie" is a 1983 arcade game developed by Taito and distributed in the United States by Midway Manufacturing. The game features a cartoonish depiction of Arnold Schwarzenegger as the titular character, who must rescue his girlfriend from the clutches of an evil scientist.  Players control Arnie as he battles through various stages, employing a variety of weaponry and fighting techniques. While "Arnie" was a commercial success, it was criticized for its simplistic gameplay and repetition. Despite its flaws, the game stands as a unique piece of video game history, reflecting the popularity of action films and celebrity culture in the 1980s.
Forbes Galleries: Forbes Galleries, established in 1998, is an art gallery located in Manhattan, New York City. The gallery is known for exhibiting works by prominent contemporary artists, often with a focus on photography and social commentary. Founded by the Forbes family, renowned for their business magazine, Forbes Galleries aims to showcase exceptional artistic talent while promoting understanding and dialogue around significant social and cultural issues. The gallery has hosted numerous exhibitions featuring renowned photographers such as Annie Leibovitz, David LaChapelle, and Steve McCurry, solidifying its reputation as a platform for high-quality contemporary art.
Gerhard Andrey: Gerhard Andrey (1906-1990) was a Swiss architect and city planner known for his influential role in the development of modern urbanism in Switzerland. He is particularly recognized for his work on the "New Town" of Zurich-Altstetten, designed in the 1950s and featuring a unique blend of residential, commercial, and public spaces. Andrey was also a key figure in the Swiss Werkbund, a movement advocating for functional and aesthetic design in architecture and everyday life. His career spanned several decades, leaving a lasting mark on Swiss urban landscapes and contributing to the evolution of modern architecture principles.
Suzanne P. Clark: Suzanne P. Clark is an American businesswoman who has served as the president and CEO of the American Society of Association Executives (ASAE) since 2016. Prior to her role at ASAE, Clark held leadership positions at several organizations, including the American Red Cross, where she served as president of the National Capital Region from 2010 to 2015. Clark is known for her advocacy for the association and non-profit sectors, and she has been recognized for her leadership in promoting diversity and inclusion. She is a graduate of Georgetown University and holds an MBA from the University of Maryland.
USS Phelps: USS *Phelps* (DD-360) was a Clemson-class destroyer commissioned in the United States Navy in 1921. She served during World War I and World War II, participating in numerous naval battles and operations. Notable actions include the Battle of the Atlantic, where she escorted convoys and engaged in anti-submarine warfare. Decommissioned in 1946, the *Phelps* was later sold for scrap.  The ship was named after William D. Phelps, a Medal of Honor recipient who served in the U.S. Navy during the Spanish-American War.
Charles of Bourbon Visiting St Peter's B: "Charles of Bourbon Visiting St. Peter's Basilica" is a 16th-century painting by the Italian artist Sebastiano del Piombo, currently housed in the National Gallery, London. The work depicts Charles of Bourbon, a prominent military figure and Constable of France, during his pilgrimage to Rome in 1527. The painting captures the grandeur of St. Peter's Basilica, a significant landmark in the Roman Catholic Church, and showcases the artist's mastery of portraying both architecture and human figures. Notably, the painting was commissioned by the influential Cardinal Lorenzo Pucci, highlighting the importance of Charles of Bourbon as a historical figure within the context of the Italian Renaissance.
Project X (2012 film): "Project X" is a 2012 American comedy film directed by Nima Nourizadeh. The film follows three high school friends who decide to throw a massive house party to gain popularity. Despite initially aiming for a modest gathering, the party quickly spirals out of control, leading to widespread chaos and destruction. The film was a box office success, grossing over $100 million worldwide on a budget of $12 million. While praised for its realistic depiction of teenage partying, "Project X" also faced criticism for its portrayal of excessive drinking, drug use, and violence.
Japan at the 2015 Summer Universiade: Japan hosted the 2015 Summer Universiade in Gwangju, South Korea, from July 3 to 14.  The Japanese delegation achieved significant success, securing a total of 115 medals, including 37 gold, 36 silver, and 42 bronze. Notably, they excelled in Judo, securing 10 gold medals, and in swimming, where they claimed 8 gold medals.  The impressive performance solidified Japan's position as a leading sporting nation in the Universiade, contributing to its growing legacy in international athletics.
The Exile (1931 film): "The Exile" (1931) is a pre-Code American drama film directed by Josef von Sternberg and starring Marlene Dietrich and Lionel Atwill.  The film, a loose adaptation of the play "The Exile" by Lajos Biro, tells the story of a glamorous cabaret singer (Dietrich) forced to flee her homeland after becoming entangled in a political scandal.  Noted for its striking cinematography, its exploration of themes of love, betrayal, and political intrigue, "The Exile" solidified Dietrich's star power and demonstrated Sternberg's mastery of visual storytelling.  The film's release was met with mixed reviews, with some critics praising its artistic merit while others criticized its melodramatic plot and pacing.
The Snowshoe Trail: "The Snowshoe Trail" is a 220-mile (354 km) long-distance hiking trail located in the White Mountains of New Hampshire, United States. Developed in the late 1970s by the Appalachian Mountain Club, the trail traverses diverse terrain, from dense forests and alpine meadows to rocky summits and rugged ridgelines. The trail's name, "Snowshoe," alludes to its accessibility during winter months, when snowshoes or skis are often necessary for traversing its challenging sections. Though not as well-known as the Appalachian Trail, the Snowshoe Trail offers a unique and strenuous hiking experience, attracting outdoor enthusiasts seeking solitude and stunning mountain scenery.
Pyrrocoma racemosa: *Pyrrocoma racemosa*, commonly known as the **racemose goldenweed**, is a perennial wildflower native to the western United States and Canada. It is a member of the Asteraceae family and is characterized by its bright yellow daisy-like flowers that bloom from July to September.  This plant thrives in open, dry habitats, particularly on rocky slopes and grasslands. Its scientific name, "racemosa," refers to the flower's clustered arrangement, resembling a raceme.  *Pyrrocoma racemosa* is an important food source for various pollinators, contributing to the biodiversity of its native ecosystems.
Beritan G\u00fcne\u015f Alt\u0131n: "Beritan Güneş Altın" (born 1989) is a Turkish-Kurdish politician and activist known for her role in the Kurdish struggle for self-determination. Born in Diyarbakır, Turkey, she joined the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) in her youth and became active in the organization's political wing, the Kurdistan Communities Union (KCK). Güneş Altın gained notoriety for her involvement in the KCK's efforts to establish local self-governance in Kurdish-populated areas of Turkey, advocating for increased autonomy and cultural rights for the Kurdish people. She has been detained by Turkish authorities on multiple occasions for her political activities, and her case has drawn attention to the ongoing Kurdish-Turkish conflict and the limitations on freedom of expression in Turkey.
Mercury FM: Mercury FM is a commercial radio station based in Nottingham, England, broadcasting to the East Midlands region. It launched in 1995 and has become a prominent local station, known for its popular music format, local news, and community engagement. The station is part of the Bauer Media Group, one of the largest media companies in the United Kingdom, and its programming includes a mix of contemporary hits, classic tracks, and local presenters. Mercury FM has played a significant role in shaping the media landscape of the East Midlands, providing local entertainment and information to its audience.
Higashi-Matsuyama Station: Higashi-Matsuyama Station is a railway station located in Higashi-Matsuyama, Saitama Prefecture, Japan, served by the Seibu Shinjuku Line. The station, opened in 1915, is a major transportation hub in the city, serving both local commuters and tourists visiting the nearby historic sites. It is characterized by its distinctive brick architecture and features a spacious concourse with numerous shops and restaurants. The station has been featured in various films and television series, further boosting its cultural significance.
The BFG (1989 film): "The BFG" (1989) is an animated fantasy film adaptation of Roald Dahl's 1982 novel of the same name. Directed by  **Dave Sproat** and **Brian Cosgrove**, the film features the voices of **David Jason** as the friendly giant, the BFG, and **Amanda Root** as Sophie, a young girl who befriends him. Released in the United Kingdom on July 14, 1989, the film garnered critical acclaim for its faithfulness to the source material, its animation style, and its captivating storytelling. Notably, "The BFG" also received a BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film in 1990, solidifying its place as a beloved adaptation of Dahl's work.
Doris Stump: Doris Stump (1911-1998) was a prominent American educator and advocate for early childhood education. She dedicated her career to developing and promoting innovative educational methods, particularly in the field of preschool education. Known for her work in developing the "Stump Method" of teaching, which emphasized hands-on learning and individual attention, she established the Doris Stump School in 1947, a groundbreaking preschool that became a model for early childhood education across the United States. Stump's influence on the field was significant, leading to a shift towards child-centered learning and the recognition of preschool as an essential stage in early development.
\u017bytkiejmy: Żytkiejmy is a village located in the Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship in northeastern Poland. The village has a rich history, dating back to the 14th century, when it was established as a part of the Teutonic Knights State. In the 19th century, Żytkiejmy became part of Prussia and experienced significant growth. After World War II, the village was incorporated into Poland as part of the post-war territorial changes. Today, Żytkiejmy is a peaceful rural community known for its picturesque surroundings and a historic church, a testament to its long and varied past.
Amazonian antshrike: The Amazonian antshrike (Thamnomanes ardesiacus) is a species of bird in the Thamnophilidae family. It is found in the Amazon rainforest of South America, specifically in Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela. This small, insectivorous bird is characterized by its gray plumage, long, pointed tail, and distinctive song. The Amazonian antshrike plays an important role in the rainforest ecosystem by controlling insect populations. It often associates with army ants, following their foraging trails to catch insects that are disturbed by the ants.
Band of the Brigade of Gurkhas: The Band of the Brigade of Gurkhas is the official military band of the Brigade of Gurkhas, a unit of the British Army. Founded in 1848, the band has a long and distinguished history, having served in numerous conflicts and ceremonial events around the world. Notable features of the band include its unique blend of traditional Gurkha music with Western musical styles, its distinctive uniform, and its exceptional musical skill. The band has performed at major events, such as the Queen's Birthday Parade and the Royal Edinburgh Military Tattoo, showcasing the musical heritage and traditions of the Gurkha regiments.
Peter Howson: Peter Howson (born 1958) is a renowned Australian painter best known for his expressive and often controversial figurative works. His art frequently explores themes of social alienation, poverty, and the human condition, often depicted through gritty and realistic portrayals of individuals from the margins of society. Howson's early career was marked by a stint as a boxer before he dedicated himself to painting in the late 1970s. His work has been exhibited extensively in Australia and internationally, including at the National Gallery of Australia, the Tate Gallery in London, and the Museum of Contemporary Art in Sydney. He received the Archibald Prize, Australia's most prestigious portraiture award, in 1992.
Jewish Standard: The *Jewish Standard* is a weekly newspaper serving the Jewish community in Bergen County, New Jersey, and the surrounding area. Founded in 1919 by Rabbi Judah M. Eisenberg, it has evolved from a local religious publication to a comprehensive news source covering local, national, and international Jewish affairs. The paper is known for its coverage of Jewish life in the region, including news, culture, and community events. Notable contributors have included renowned Jewish thinkers and writers, further enhancing its reputation as a leading voice for the Jewish community in New Jersey.
Grant Stewart (musician): Grant Stewart is a Canadian singer-songwriter and musician, known for his contributions to the Canadian music scene. He began his musical journey in the early 1990s, releasing his debut album, "The Long and Winding Road," in 1993. Throughout his career, Stewart has released multiple albums, including "A Little Bit of Heaven" (1996) and "The Journey Continues" (2001), showcasing his unique blend of folk, rock, and country influences. Notably, Stewart has collaborated with renowned Canadian musicians such as Anne Murray and The Rankin Family, contributing to his recognition and popularity within the country's music landscape.
Llanddulas: Llanddulas is a village and community in Conwy County Borough, Wales, situated on the North Wales coast. The name, meaning "Church of St. Teglas," reflects its history as a site of religious significance dating back to the 6th century. The village is known for its picturesque beach, which attracts tourists and locals alike, as well as its proximity to the historic Conwy Castle, a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Llanddulas is also home to the ancient Llanddulas Church, a Grade I listed building, and a number of other historic sites, including the remains of a medieval manor house.
Alpha Motor Corporation: Alpha Motor Corporation is an American electric vehicle manufacturer founded in 2018, headquartered in Los Angeles, California. The company focuses on producing affordable and stylish electric pickup trucks and SUVs, aiming to capture a market share in the burgeoning EV industry. Alpha Motor Corporation has gained attention for its unique designs, including the retro-inspired "Ace" pickup truck and the futuristic "Saga" SUV. The company is currently in the development and production stages, with plans to release its first models in the coming years.
Zugdidi Municipality: Zugdidi Municipality is a municipality in the Samegrelo-Zemo Svaneti region of western Georgia. Located in the fertile Colchis Plain, it encompasses the city of Zugdidi, the administrative center of the region, and surrounding villages. The municipality has a rich history, dating back to the Kingdom of Colchis, with notable historical sites like the Dadiani Palace, a former residence of the Dadiani dynasty.  Zugdidi Municipality is significant for its role in Georgian culture, particularly as the center of the Samegrelo region, known for its distinct traditions and folklore. The area is also known for its agricultural production, including tea, citrus fruits, and vegetables.
Chris Pearce (politician): Chris Pearce is a prominent Australian politician known for his service in the Australian House of Representatives. He represented the Division of Dawson, located in Queensland, as a member of the Liberal Party from 2004 to 2016. During his tenure, Pearce held significant roles within the government, including Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for Resources, Energy and Tourism from 2007 to 2009 and Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for Regional Australia from 2009 to 2010.  His political career was marked by his advocacy for regional development and the resource sector.
Maharaja's Sanskrit College, Mysore: The Maharaja's Sanskrit College, Mysore, established in 1891 by Maharaja Chamarajendra Wadiyar, is a prestigious institution dedicated to the study and preservation of Sanskrit literature and culture. Located in Mysore, Karnataka, India, the college boasts a rich history and has played a pivotal role in promoting Sanskrit scholarship and education. Notable figures associated with the college include renowned scholars like R. Narasimhachar and A.R. Krishnasastry, who have contributed significantly to the advancement of Sanskrit studies. The college continues to attract students from across India and abroad, fostering a vibrant academic environment and upholding the legacy of Sanskrit tradition.
USS Kittiwake: USS *Kittiwake* (SSN-709) was a Los Angeles-class nuclear-powered attack submarine that served in the United States Navy from 1980 to 2009. Launched in 1979 and commissioned the following year, the vessel participated in numerous operations, including the Persian Gulf War and the Cold War.  Upon decommissioning, the *Kittiwake* was intentionally sunk off the coast of Grand Cayman in 2011, becoming an artificial reef and popular dive site. The *Kittiwake* is now a significant attraction for scuba divers, offering a unique opportunity to explore the preserved remains of a Cold War-era submarine.
Lower Silvermine River Wetlands: The Lower Silvermine River Wetlands, located in San Mateo County, California, are a significant wetland ecosystem that supports a diverse array of flora and fauna. The wetlands, formed by the confluence of the Silvermine River and San Francisco Bay, serve as a critical habitat for numerous bird species, including migratory waterfowl, as well as fish, amphibians, and mammals. The wetlands have a rich history of human use, having been utilized for agriculture and recreation for centuries. However, the area has faced threats from development, pollution, and invasive species, leading to conservation efforts to protect this valuable resource.
Atherstone Town Football Club is a semi-professional football club based in Atherstone, Warwickshire, England. Founded in 1921, the club currently competes in the Midland Football League Premier Division. Notable players from Atherstone include former England international David Johnson, who began his career at the club. Known as the "Adders," they have played at their home ground, Sheepy Road, since 1950. They have won the Warwickshire Senior Cup on several occasions, most recently in 2002, and have also enjoyed notable success in the FA Cup, reaching the First Round Proper in 1946-47 and 1989-90.
Fusinus bifrons: *Fusinus bifrons* is a species of predatory sea snail, a marine gastropod mollusk in the family Fusinidae. This species is commonly known as the "two-faced spindle snail" due to its distinctive shell shape with two distinct, elongated, pointed ends. It is found in the eastern Atlantic Ocean, ranging from the Mediterranean Sea to the British Isles.  *Fusinus bifrons* prefers sandy bottoms and rocky habitats at depths between 10 and 100 meters. The species has been studied for its role in the marine ecosystem and as a potential indicator of environmental change.
Talk About (song): "Talk About" is a song by American singer-songwriter Miley Cyrus, released in 2013 as part of her fourth studio album, *Bangerz*. The song, written by Cyrus, Mike Will Made It, and Theron Thomas, explores themes of heartbreak and emotional turmoil, showcasing Cyrus' evolving musical style toward a more mature and experimental sound. "Talk About" was praised for its introspective lyrics and its innovative production, featuring a blend of pop, hip-hop, and electronic influences. The song peaked at number 42 on the US Billboard Hot 100 chart, becoming another successful single from the *Bangerz* album.
1991 Basildon District Council election: The 1991 Basildon District Council election took place on May 2, 1991, to elect members of Basildon District Council in Essex, England. The election saw the Labour Party gain a majority of seats on the council, taking control from the Conservative Party. This marked a significant shift in local politics, with Labour achieving a landslide victory and ousting the Conservatives who had held control for several years prior. This election reflected a growing national trend of Labour gaining ground in local elections, signaling a potential shift in the political landscape at the time.
Belon'i Tsiribihina (district): Belon'i Tsiribihina is a district in the Menabe region of Madagascar. It is located in the western part of the country, bordering the Mozambique Channel. The district is known for its fertile land, which is primarily used for agriculture, particularly the cultivation of rice, maize, and cassava. It is also home to the Tsiribihina River, a significant waterway that provides irrigation and transportation opportunities.  The district has a long history, with its population consisting primarily of the Sakalava ethnic group. Notable features include the Tsingy de Bemaraha National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site known for its unique limestone formations.
Hell Is in Your Head: "Hell Is in Your Head" is a popular phrase used to express the idea that personal suffering, whether physical or emotional, is often self-inflicted or a product of one's own perception. This concept has roots in various philosophical and religious traditions, including Stoicism and Buddhism, which emphasize the importance of controlling one's thoughts and emotions to achieve peace and happiness.  The phrase gained widespread popularity in the 1960s and 1970s as part of the counterculture movement, particularly within the psychedelic and New Age communities. It has since become a common saying used in self-help literature and popular culture, emphasizing the power of individual perspective in shaping our experience of reality.
Trump International Hotel and Tower (Dub: Trump International Hotel and Tower Dubai is a luxury residential and hotel tower located in Dubai Marina, United Arab Emirates. Developed by The Trump Organization in partnership with Damac Properties, the 63-story tower opened in 2012. It features 282 luxury residences, a 177-room hotel, and a range of amenities including a spa, swimming pool, and restaurants. The tower's design, inspired by the "wave" motif, has been praised for its sleek, contemporary aesthetic. While the hotel and residences have been popular destinations, the property has also been the subject of controversy due to its association with former US President Donald Trump.
Buriram Hospital: Buriram Hospital is a major public hospital in Buriram, Thailand, serving the province and surrounding areas. Founded in 1909 as a small dispensary, the hospital has grown significantly over the years, becoming a regional center for healthcare. Buriram Hospital is known for its wide range of medical services, including emergency care, surgery, and specialized treatments. The hospital is a vital part of the Thai healthcare system, providing essential medical care to the local population. It has also played a significant role in training medical professionals and advancing medical research in the region.
Kartena Hillfort: Kartena Hillfort, located in Lithuania, is an Iron Age archaeological site dating back to the 1st century AD. This hillfort, situated on a strategically important hilltop, features a complex system of fortifications including ramparts, ditches, and a central courtyard. Excavations have revealed evidence of human settlement, including pottery, tools, and remnants of buildings, providing valuable insights into the lives and culture of people living in the region during the Iron Age. While its exact function remains a subject of debate, Kartena Hillfort likely served as a defensive stronghold and a center of community life.
Alex Morgan (jetski racer): Alex Morgan is a professional American jet ski racer known for her competitive spirit and impressive skill. She made her professional debut in 2012 and quickly gained recognition for her accomplishments in the Pro-Am and Pro-Women classes.  Morgan has secured multiple championships and podium finishes in prestigious competitions like the IJSBA World Finals and the US National Championships.  She is regarded as a leading figure in the sport and inspires aspiring jet ski racers, particularly women, with her dedication and achievements.
Depletion and enhancement modes: Depletion and enhancement modes refer to the two primary operational modes of field-effect transistors (FETs), a crucial component in modern electronics. In **depletion mode**, the FET operates with a channel already present, and an applied voltage depletes this channel, modulating current flow. This mode is typically found in older transistors. In contrast, **enhancement mode** FETs begin with a closed channel. Applying a voltage to the gate "enhances" the channel, allowing current to flow. Enhancement mode transistors are the most common type used today, found in a wide range of applications, from integrated circuits to power electronics. These two modes offer different characteristics, influencing the design and functionality of circuits incorporating FETs.
Kuttrapathirikai: "Kuttrapathirikai" (Tamil: குற்றபதிரிக்கை) is a 1980 Tamil-language Indian film directed by K. Balachander. The film stars Kamal Haasan, Sridevi, and Rajinikanth, and revolves around a complex story of betrayal, revenge, and justice. Kuttrapathirikai was a commercial success and became one of the most popular films of its time. The film garnered critical acclaim for its captivating narrative, compelling performances, and Balachander's trademark exploration of social issues.  It also marked a significant turning point in the careers of Kamal Haasan and Rajinikanth, solidifying their positions as leading stars in Tamil cinema.
The Sun Shines Brighter: "The Sun Shines Brighter" is a 1953 novel by the American author, Taylor Caldwell. Set in the early 20th century, the story centers on the lives of the MacAllister family, immigrants from Ireland who strive to build a better life for themselves in the bustling streets of New York City. The novel explores themes of ambition, love, loss, and the relentless pursuit of the American Dream. Caldwell's vivid descriptions of New York City and her exploration of the complexities of human relationships contribute to the book's enduring popularity. "The Sun Shines Brighter" is considered a classic of American literature and has been adapted for both stage and screen.
Richard Phipson: Richard Phipson (1916-1994) was a British actor known for his extensive stage career, particularly in Shakespearean roles. His early career was marked by his work with the renowned Old Vic company, where he performed alongside Laurence Olivier and Vivien Leigh. Phipson's distinctive baritone voice and commanding stage presence made him a popular and respected figure in British theater. He also appeared in numerous television and film roles, including a memorable turn as a Roman centurion in the 1960s epic "The Fall of the Roman Empire."
The New Oscar Pettiford Sextet: "The New Oscar Pettiford Sextet" was a prominent jazz ensemble formed in 1953 by the renowned bassist and composer Oscar Pettiford. The sextet, featuring notable musicians like trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie, saxophonist Sonny Rollins, and pianist Horace Silver, was known for its innovative blend of bebop and blues influences. Their musical collaborations resulted in a distinctive sound that showcased Pettiford's virtuoso bass playing and innovative arrangements. The group's brief but impactful career was marked by influential recordings and performances, solidifying their place as a key contributor to the evolution of jazz in the 1950s.
John Avery McIlhenny: John Avery McIlhenny (1883–1957) was an American businessman and the third-generation owner of the McIlhenny Company, famous for its Tabasco brand hot sauce. Born into the family that founded the company in 1868, McIlhenny took over as president in 1917, overseeing a period of significant expansion and diversification. Under his leadership, the company introduced new product lines, modernized its production facilities, and established a global distribution network. McIlhenny's dedication to quality and innovative marketing strategies helped to solidify Tabasco's position as a household name, making it a prominent brand in the food industry.
A. Devitt Vanech: A. Devitt Vanech (1897–1973) was an American lawyer and jurist who served as the 10th Solicitor General of the United States from 1946 to 1949. He was a prominent figure in the Democratic Party and a close confidant of President Harry S. Truman. During his tenure as Solicitor General, Vanech argued several significant cases before the Supreme Court, including the landmark case of *Brown v. Board of Education*, which overturned segregation in public schools.  Prior to his service in the Department of Justice, he held various positions in the New York State government, including Attorney General from 1943 to 1946.
Faydee: Faydee is a Lebanese-Australian singer and songwriter known for his contributions to the Arabic pop music scene. Born in Beirut, Lebanon, Faydee emigrated to Australia with his family in 1992. He began his musical career in 2007, releasing his debut album "Albi Ma'ak" which garnered significant popularity in the Middle East. Faydee is renowned for his energetic performances and collaborations with artists such as Nancy Ajram and Mohamed Hamaki, solidifying his place as a prominent figure in contemporary Arabic music. He continues to release music and perform internationally, captivating audiences with his distinctive blend of pop, dance, and traditional Arabic influences.
The Orion Loop: "The Orion Loop" is a hypothetical astronomical structure proposed by some scientists as a possible explanation for the observed distribution of stars in the Milky Way galaxy. The concept, developed in the 1970s, suggests a large, ring-like structure of gas and dust, centered on the constellation Orion, that influences star formation. This theory remains speculative and controversial, lacking strong observational evidence. However, it has spurred further investigation into the complex structure and evolution of our galaxy, particularly the role of large-scale gas dynamics in star formation. While not widely accepted within the astronomical community, the Orion Loop concept serves as an interesting example of scientific inquiry and the ongoing pursuit to understand the universe.
Kashk bademjan: Kashk bademjan is a traditional Iranian dish consisting of eggplant, walnut paste, and whey.  This flavorful and hearty dish, often served with flatbread, has a long history in Persia, dating back to ancient times.  The combination of smoky eggplant, nutty walnut paste, and tangy whey creates a complex flavor profile, representing a typical interplay of sweet, sour, and savory tastes often found in Persian cuisine.  Notable variations include the addition of herbs like mint, or the substitution of yogurt for whey.  Kashk bademjan remains a popular comfort food in Iran and other parts of the Middle East.
List of compositions by Alexander Borodi: "List of compositions by Alexander Borodin" is a comprehensive catalog of musical works by the Russian composer Alexander Borodin (1833-1887). The list includes his most famous works, such as the symphony "In the Steppes of Central Asia" and the opera "Prince Igor," as well as lesser-known compositions like his quartets, piano pieces, and vocal works. Borodin, a chemist by profession, was a member of the "Mighty Five," a group of Russian composers who sought to create a distinctly Russian musical style. The list provides insights into Borodin's creative output, highlighting the breadth of his musical talent and his significant contributions to Russian musical history.
Ambrose of Belaya Krinitsa: Ambrose of Belaya Krinitsa (1797-1873) was a prominent Russian Orthodox Old Believer leader who played a key role in the revival of the Old Believer movement in the 19th century. He was born as Alexey Savelyevich Titov in the village of Belaya Krinitsa in Bessarabia and later became known as Ambrose after becoming a priest. Known for his strong advocacy for Old Believer beliefs and practices, Ambrose established the Belokrinitskaya Agreement in 1846, which aimed to unify various Old Believer groups under a single hierarchical structure. This agreement proved crucial in the revival of the Old Believer faith and led to the establishment of the Belokrinitsky Old Rite, one of the most influential branches of Old Believer Christianity.
Kato Symi: Kato Symi, also known as Lower Symi, is a historic town and port on the Greek island of Symi. It is renowned for its distinctive neoclassical architecture, characterized by colorful, sponge-like buildings lining the harbor. The town's history is intertwined with the sponge industry, which thrived in Symi during the 19th century. Notable figures associated with Kato Symi include the sponge diver and merchant Ioannis Kassianos, whose legacy is celebrated in the town's Kassianos House museum. Kato Symi is a popular tourist destination, attracting visitors drawn to its picturesque harbor, traditional architecture, and rich cultural heritage.
Castelletto sopra Ticino: Castelletto sopra Ticino is a comune (municipality) in the Province of Novara in the Italian region Piedmont, located about 80 kilometers (50 mi) northeast of Turin and approximately 15 kilometers (9 mi) southwest of Novara. The village sits on the right bank of the Ticino river, overlooking a large plain.  The area is rich in history, with archaeological evidence dating back to the Roman period. The village's name, "Castelletto sopra Ticino," translates to "Little Castle above the Ticino," reflecting its strategic position and historical significance.  The village features the Chiesa di San Martino, a medieval church, along with the Castello di Castelletto, a castle that played a role in the local history of the area.
Pupo Line: The Pupo Line, also known as the Pupo Tunnel, was a planned rail tunnel connecting the cities of Naples and Rome in Italy. Proposed in the early 20th century by Italian engineer Luigi Pupo, the tunnel was intended to provide a faster and more efficient route between the two major cities.  Despite extensive studies and the completion of preliminary construction work, the project was ultimately abandoned due to various factors, including the outbreak of World War I, economic challenges, and competing infrastructure projects. The Pupo Line remains a fascinating example of ambitious infrastructure planning in early 20th-century Italy, though it never came to fruition.
Mus\u00e9e des Beaux-Arts de Dijon: The Musée des Beaux-Arts de Dijon is a renowned art museum located in Dijon, France, housing a vast collection spanning from the Middle Ages to the 20th century. Established in 1787, it initially held the possessions of the Duke of Burgundy and later expanded to include works from various periods, including prominent pieces by artists like Rogier van der Weyden, Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot, and Gustave Courbet. The museum's collection encompasses a diverse range of art forms, including paintings, sculptures, decorative arts, and archaeological artifacts, making it a significant cultural hub in Dijon and a testament to the region's artistic heritage.
Felix Passlack: Felix Passlack (born 1998) is a German professional footballer who plays as a midfielder for Bundesliga club VfL Bochum. He began his career in the youth academy of Borussia Dortmund, where he progressed through the ranks and made his professional debut in 2016. Passlack has also had loan spells at Hoffenheim and Norwich City, gaining experience in the Bundesliga and Premier League.  He is known for his versatility, capable of playing in various midfield positions, and his ability to contribute defensively and offensively.  Passlack's career has been marked by his consistent presence within the German football scene, demonstrating a steady progression as a promising talent.
Carsten K\u00f6nneker: Carsten Könneker is a German composer, conductor, and music theorist, born in 1967. His work has been performed worldwide by renowned orchestras like the Berlin Philharmonic, the NDR Symphony Orchestra, and the Los Angeles Philharmonic. Könneker is known for his innovative use of computer technology in composition, exploring the interplay between acoustic and electronic sounds. He is also a prominent figure in the field of music theory, having published several books and articles on topics such as serialism, spectral music, and microtonal systems. His compositions have been praised for their intellectual depth, technical virtuosity, and sonic beauty.
T\u00edsek: "Tísek" is a Czech word meaning "distress" or "anguish." It is often used in literature and art to convey intense emotional states. In the context of Czech literature, "Tísek" is associated with the literary movement known as "Czech Modernism," which emerged in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. This movement was characterized by a focus on exploring themes of alienation, despair, and the search for meaning in a rapidly changing world. Notable Czech authors who have explored the theme of "Tísek" in their works include Franz Kafka, Karel Čapek, and Bohumil Hrabal. Their works often depict the anxieties and inner turmoil of individuals grappling with the challenges of modern life, making "Tísek" a recurring motif in Czech literature and a significant element in understanding the cultural landscape of the country.
Jetex (company): Jetex is a global private aviation company headquartered in Dubai, United Arab Emirates. Established in 2005 by Adel Al-Redha, Jetex provides a wide range of services for private jet travelers, including fueling, ground handling, and aircraft management. The company operates across 40 locations worldwide, serving both private and commercial aircraft. Jetex has played a significant role in developing the private aviation industry in the Middle East and beyond, contributing to the region's emergence as a major hub for luxury travel.
U.S. Route 60 in Missouri: U.S. Route 60 in Missouri is a major east-west highway traversing the state from the Mississippi River in St. Louis County to the Kentucky border near the city of Charleston. Established in 1926 as part of the original U.S. Highway system, the route originally ran through downtown St. Louis. However, in 1954, the highway was rerouted to avoid the city center, running along the Interstate 44 corridor. Significant portions of U.S. Route 60 in Missouri coincide with other major highways, including Interstate 44, U.S. Route 63, and Missouri Route 13. The route is a vital connection for commerce and transportation throughout the state, serving major cities like St. Louis, Jefferson City, and Columbia.
Ivan Margary: Ivan Margary (1818-1888) was a British surveyor and engineer known for his extensive exploration and mapping of the Caucasus region in the 19th century. He traveled extensively throughout the region, traversing rugged terrain and documenting its geography, topography, and infrastructure. Margary's meticulous surveys and detailed maps were crucial for British understanding of the Caucasus, contributing to their knowledge of the region's strategic importance during a period of geopolitical tension. He is particularly remembered for his explorations of the Darial Gorge and the Caucasus Mountains, documenting these previously uncharted areas with unprecedented accuracy.
Strode's College: Strode's College is a further education college located in Street, Somerset, England. Established in 1976, the college offers a wide range of vocational and academic courses to students aged 16 and above. Notably, Strode's College is known for its strong partnerships with local businesses and industries, providing students with practical experience and relevant skills.  The college also boasts modern facilities, including a dedicated sports center and a well-equipped library.
Cass-Clay: "Cass-Clay" refers to a joint county government located in the Red River Valley of North Dakota, United States. Established in 1919, the government serves both Cass County and Clay County, encompassing the Fargo-Moorhead metropolitan area. This unique structure allows for efficient collaboration on shared services like law enforcement, planning, and infrastructure development. The Cass-Clay government is notable for its history of innovation and efficiency, exemplified by its pioneering efforts in regional planning and the creation of the Fargo-Moorhead Metropolitan Council of Governments in 1966.
Chestnut-bellied guan: The Chestnut-bellied Guan (**Penelope ochrogaster**) is a large, ground-dwelling bird native to the humid forests of western South America, primarily found in Colombia and Ecuador. This species, distinguished by its chestnut-colored underparts and distinctive blue facial skin, is known for its loud, trumpeting calls that echo through the forest. Chestnut-bellied Guans are primarily frugivores, playing an important role in seed dispersal throughout their habitat. While their population is considered stable, the species is threatened by deforestation and habitat loss, highlighting the need for conservation efforts to protect this unique and beautiful bird.
Egerton Dock: Egerton Dock is a former dock in Birkenhead, England, located on the River Mersey. Constructed in the late 19th century and operational until the 1970s, it played a significant role in the region's maritime trade. The dock was named after William Egerton, 1st Baron Egerton of Tatton, the then chairman of the Mersey Docks and Harbour Board. Notable features of the dock include its large size, accommodating a variety of vessels, and its connection to the Birkenhead Docks system, enabling efficient cargo handling.  Following its closure, the area was redeveloped into a mixed-use area including residential and commercial properties.
Diacyclops thomasi: *Diacyclops thomasi* is a species of cyclopoid copepod, a small crustacean found in freshwater habitats. This species is particularly notable for its wide geographical distribution, occurring in North America, Europe, and Asia.  *Diacyclops thomasi* is considered a key component of the zooplankton community in many lakes and ponds, playing a crucial role in the food web as a primary consumer of algae and other small organisms. Its abundance and importance in these ecosystems have made it a subject of extensive research, particularly in the fields of ecology and limnology.
Broadchurch series 2: "Broadchurch series 2" is the second season of the British crime drama television series *Broadchurch*, which aired on ITV in 2014. Following the arrest of Joe Miller for the murder of Danny Latimer in the first season, the second season explores the aftermath of the trial and the ongoing investigation into the disappearance of a local woman,  Beth Latimer's mother, Susan Wright. The season features returning cast members Olivia Colman as Detective Inspector Ellie Miller, David Tennant as Detective Inspector Alec Hardy, and Arthur Darvill as Reverend Paul Coates, alongside new characters played by actors like Eve Myles and Marianne Jean-Baptiste. The series delves into themes of grief, family secrets, and the impact of trauma on a small community.
Guilford, Maine: Guilford, Maine, is a town in Piscataquis County, Maine, United States. Founded in 1812, the town takes its name from Guilford, Connecticut, and was incorporated in 1816. Situated along the Piscataquis River, Guilford is known for its scenic beauty and its historical significance, having played a role in the lumber industry during the 19th century. The town is home to several notable landmarks, including the Guilford Historical Society Museum, which showcases the area's rich past.
2007 Boston Borough Council election: The 2007 Boston Borough Council election was held on May 3, 2007, to elect members of Boston Borough Council in Lincolnshire, England. The election saw a significant shift in the political landscape of the borough, with the Labour Party losing its overall majority and the Conservative Party making gains. The Conservatives gained 11 seats, taking control of the council for the first time since 1999. Labour lost 10 seats, leaving them with 16 seats. The election was seen as a sign of the growing popularity of the Conservatives in the area, and a reflection of public dissatisfaction with the Labour government's performance at the national level.
Matilda De Angelis: Matilda De Angelis (born September 11, 1995) is an Italian actress known for her roles in both film and television. She rose to prominence in 2019 with her breakout role in the Italian television series "Tutto può cambiare." Her performance earned her a nomination for Best Actress at the 76th Venice Film Festival.  De Angelis has since starred in several successful Italian films, including "The First King" (2019) and "The Vice of Hope" (2020).  Her international recognition further expanded with her portrayal of Anna in the 2022 HBO miniseries "The Undoing."
WTJZ (AM): WTJZ (AM) is a radio station broadcasting on 1400 kHz in Jacksonville, Florida. Licensed to Jacksonville Beach, it began broadcasting in 1959 as WQIK, later changing its call sign to WTJZ in 1998. Originally airing a country music format, WTJZ switched to a talk radio format in the 2000s and currently focuses on conservative talk shows. The station's studios and transmitter are located in Jacksonville Beach.
Create with Garfield: "Create with Garfield" is a digital drawing and animation platform developed by Paws, Inc., the company that owns the rights to the Garfield comic strip. Launched in 2019, the platform allows users to create original artwork featuring Garfield and his friends. Users can choose from a library of pre-made backgrounds, characters, and props, or upload their own images. The platform is free to use and has been praised for its accessibility and user-friendly interface, making it popular with both children and adults. It features a community aspect where users can share their creations and interact with other artists.
Nova Cana\u00e3 do Norte: Nova Canaã do Norte is a municipality located in the state of Mato Grosso, Brazil. Founded in 1992, the city is situated in the northern region of the state, near the border with the state of Rondônia. Nova Canaã do Norte is known for its agricultural production, particularly in the cultivation of soybeans and corn. The city's economy also benefits from the extraction of timber and mining activities. The municipality's rapid growth has attracted a diverse population, including migrants from other parts of Brazil and neighboring countries.
Internet Explorer 6: Internet Explorer 6 (IE6) was a web browser released by Microsoft in August 2001 as part of Windows XP. It was the dominant browser for several years, achieving a peak market share of over 90% in 2004. IE6 was criticized for its security flaws, poor standards compliance, and lack of innovation.  Its continued usage in the mid-2000s led to the widespread adoption of workarounds and the rise of the "IE6-only" era, where web developers had to specifically cater to IE6's limitations. Microsoft finally discontinued support for IE6 in 2014.
Platinum Triangle, Anaheim: The Platinum Triangle, located in Anaheim, California, is a vibrant commercial and entertainment district known for its high concentration of hotels, restaurants, and entertainment venues. Developed in the late 20th century, the district is anchored by the Anaheim Convention Center, Disneyland Resort, and the Honda Center, attracting millions of visitors annually. Notable hotels in the Platinum Triangle include the Disneyland Hotel, the Grand Californian Hotel & Spa, and the Anaheim Marriott. The area is also home to several major shopping centers, including the Anaheim GardenWalk and the Downtown Disney District.
Awara (album): "Awara" is the debut studio album by Indian singer-songwriter Arijit Singh, released in 2014. The album, a blend of Bollywood and contemporary pop music, was a commercial success, solidifying Singh's position as a leading voice in the Indian music industry. Produced by Pritam, the album features a collection of soulful and melodious tracks, many of which became chart-toppers, including "Tum Hi Ho," "Phir Bhi Tumko Chaahunga," and "Mast Magan." "Awara" marked a significant step in Singh's career, establishing his versatility and solidifying his popularity among music lovers across generations.
Typhoon Dujuan (2003): Typhoon Dujuan (2003) was a powerful tropical cyclone that formed in the western Pacific Ocean in September 2003. It made landfall in Japan as a strong typhoon, causing significant damage and disruption. The storm's intensity peaked at 145 kilometers per hour (90 miles per hour) wind speeds, with gusts reaching as high as 195 kilometers per hour (121 miles per hour).  Dujuan caused widespread flooding and landslides, leading to several casualties and substantial economic losses. The storm's path through Japan highlighted the vulnerability of coastal communities to extreme weather events and spurred efforts to improve disaster preparedness in the region.
NASCAR Thunder 2004: *NASCAR Thunder 2004* is a 2003 stock car racing video game developed by EA Sports and published by Electronic Arts for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 2, and Xbox. It is the sixth installment in the *NASCAR Thunder* series and features an updated graphics engine, improved car physics, and a wider selection of tracks and drivers compared to previous installments. The game received generally positive reviews for its realistic gameplay and extensive career mode. Notably, it introduced the "Chase for the Cup" playoff system to the franchise, which became a prominent feature in future NASCAR games.
William L. Brandon: William L. Brandon (1924-2006) was an American author and screenwriter known for his historical novels and Westerns. Born in Alabama, Brandon moved to New York City in the 1950s, where he began his writing career. He is perhaps best known for his 1959 novel "The Ballad of the Sad Cafe," which was adapted into a film by Edward Albee in 1967. Brandon's other works include the historical novels "The Man Who Cried I Am" and "The Devil on the Mountain," and he also wrote numerous screenplays for television series such as "The Virginian" and "Bonanza." Brandon's prolific writing career spanned over four decades, and he is considered a significant figure in both the Southern Gothic and Western genres.
Intoxication (film): "Intoxication" is a 1992 French-American thriller film directed by Barbet Schroeder. The film stars Isabelle Huppert as a French woman who becomes entangled in a dangerous affair with a mysterious American businessman, portrayed by Peter Coyote. Notably, "Intoxication" garnered critical acclaim for its intense psychological drama and exploration of themes of desire, betrayal, and the complexities of human relationships. The film's striking cinematography and score contribute to its suspenseful atmosphere, and its exploration of the psychological impact of obsession on its characters remains relevant to contemporary audiences.
David Yakobashvili: David Yakobashvili is a prominent Georgian businessman and philanthropist known for his significant contributions to the development of Georgia's economy and cultural landscape. He is the founder and chairman of the board of TBC Bank, the largest commercial bank in Georgia, which he established in 1992 amidst the country's transition to a market economy.  Yakobashvili is also a major investor in various sectors, including hospitality, real estate, and media, and has played a key role in revitalizing Tbilisi's historic Old Town through his restoration projects. Notably, he founded the David Yakobashvili Foundation, dedicated to supporting cultural and educational initiatives in Georgia.
Vintage Television: Vintage television refers to television sets and programming from the past, typically encompassing the era from the 1940s to the 1980s. This period saw significant advancements in television technology, including the transition from black and white to color broadcasts, the introduction of remote control, and the development of new genres like sitcoms and soap operas.  Notable figures in early television include pioneers like Philo Farnsworth, who developed the first electronic television system, and Lucille Ball, whose iconic sitcom "I Love Lucy" helped shape the landscape of American television. Today, vintage television continues to hold cultural significance as a source of entertainment and nostalgia, with collectors and enthusiasts preserving and sharing these historical artifacts.
2 (Ned Collette album): "2" is the second studio album by Australian singer-songwriter Ned Collette, released in 2003. The album marked a departure from Collette's previous folk-rock sound, incorporating elements of electronic music and experimental production. "2" was critically acclaimed for its innovative approach and introspective lyrics, showcasing Collette's musical evolution. Notably, the album featured collaborations with renowned Australian musicians such as Mick Harvey and Evelyn Morris. While commercially less successful than his debut, "2" remains a significant work in Collette's discography, solidifying his reputation as a creative and versatile artist.
Wilson Lumpkin: Wilson Lumpkin (1799–1860) was an American politician who served as the 41st Governor of Georgia from 1835 to 1837. Born in Oglethorpe County, Georgia, Lumpkin studied law and rose through the ranks of Georgia politics, serving in the state legislature and the U.S. House of Representatives. As governor, he focused on economic development, promoting infrastructure projects like the construction of railroads. He was a vocal advocate for states' rights and opposed the expansion of federal power. After leaving office, Lumpkin remained a prominent figure in Georgia politics and served as a delegate to the 1860 Democratic National Convention.
2021 Copa Libertadores: The 2021 Copa Libertadores was the 62nd edition of the premier club football tournament in South America. The tournament, organized by CONMEBOL, saw 47 clubs from ten countries compete for the coveted title. The final was contested between Brazilian giants Palmeiras and Flamengo, with Palmeiras emerging victorious after a penalty shootout in a dramatic match played at the Estadio Centenario in Montevideo, Uruguay on November 27, 2021. This victory marked Palmeiras' third Copa Libertadores title and their second in three years.
The Buzzhorn: "The Buzzhorn" is a fictional device featured in the 1988 animated film "The Adventures of Baron Munchausen". This peculiar contraption, resembling a giant trumpet, was designed by the titular Baron Munchausen as a means of generating a powerful sound wave capable of propelling himself and his companions across vast distances.
